bs@gauss.mitre.org (Robert D. Silverman) writes:

> It does not matter. Even if factoring can be done in polynomial time
> you can still construct a key large enough to make factoring it
> prohibitively expensive. 

Correct me if I am wrong, but:

The above is true, but ignores the fact that until
one knows the characteristics of any as-yet-unknown polynomial-time
factoring method, one does not know HOW large one needs to
make the key, in order to make factoring prohibitively expensive.

